<p class="bold">Here we are.</p> 
<p>This room is wide and very tall, extending below and above where we stand - on a walkway. Bits of design and construction for future shows are often dotted around. And every time you come in, it’s different. A prop, a costume, some sketches. This is the room where designer's dreams are made real. </p>

<p>And the Paint Frame is monumental. Katy Salt can tell us more about this amazing part of Theatr Clwyd. </p>
<p>She first painted our pantomime in 2001 – she knows how the paint frame  works better than anyone.</p>
<div class="quote"><p>“So the paint frame really is just sort of hardwood battens that are attached to the back wall of the paint shop. And it's a bit like the way that an artist would stretch canvas onto a wooden frame, but in a really massive way.”</p></div>
<p>The canvases that are  stretched - they form the backdrops to shows. They frame the stories told on Theatr Clwyd’s stages , they conjure new realities. </p>

