:: 42_floorplan_story [nobr]
<p class="bold">Onstage, there are lights above and the audience below, with the world of the play alive all around you.  </p>

<p>Ah! Here is someone who lived near Mold. </p>
<p>He was recruited from school to be in a play when he was 10 – he’d  never even seen a play before! – </p>
<p>And now he’s in Hollywood – Rhys Ifans.</p>


<div class="quote">
    <p>The first time I performed on the main stage in Theatr Clwyd  was a Theatr Clwyd production of Toad, of Toad Hall, and I played a rat and I played a weasel, and it changed my life. </p>
    
    <p>Being on the stage was fantastic, because I loved the fact that you were aware of the audience, but couldn't really see them. I loved the kind of the amount of light that was on me, not in the sense that I felt seen. I just couldn't believe that, just the warmth it felt like walking into sunshine. and also the sense that when you step on stage, you set something in motion, and you have to let it run its course. You know what I mean, you can't step in and with doubts, or with, you know, say, Oh, I don't want to do this. I'm tired. You have to almost... it was... going with the flow. And you had to, like you had to succumb to the gravity of the audience and that relationship with you and it.</p>
</div>



:: 43_floorplan_story [nobr]
<p class="bold">And we have another one coming through </p>

<p>Ah! Here is someone who lived near Mold. </p>
<p>He was recruited from school to be in a play when he was 10 – he’d  never even seen a play before! – </p>
<p>And now he’s in Hollywood – Rhys Ifans.</p>

<div class="quote">
    <p>The first time I remember going to Theatr Clwyd was when I was in a production of Oliver when I was around 15 and I remember being on stage and it was total magic. It’s an amazing theatre and I’ve been very fortunate growing up in Mold. So later on, I was part of a group called Cwmni 25 and I did a lot of workshops for young people during the summer. </p>
    
</div>

<p>That’s Isabella Colby Browne  - another actor from Mold - she first performed in a production of Oliver on the stage when she was 15 - and thanks to a group called Cwmni 25, run by Gewennan Mair Jones, she now performs in Welsh and English! Da iawn Isabella</p>

:: 44_floorplan_story [nobr]
<p class="bold">From the front row, the stage is right in front of you, only  inches up.  </p>
<div class="quote"><p>“It's total immersion from the front row”</p></div>
<p>That’s Judie von der Fecht! Her and Paul are front row regulars.</p>
<div class="quote"><p>“Our first date was going to see The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy on stage at Theatr Clwyd...”</p></div>
<p>There’s Paul! They’ve been coming here since the late 1970s. They’ve been to - how many productions?</p>
<div class="quote"><p>“Hundreds and hundreds…I’ve always said that if we ever win the lottery- ... we're going to have a theatre room. And we're going to wallpaper it with our tickets.”</p></div>

:: 45_floorplan_story [nobr]

<div class="quote"><p>“The main theatre is so wonderfully intimate. No matter where you sit. It doesn't feel like when you go in there to sit down, it feels enormous, but as soon as stuff is happening on stage, there's no bad seat there... you feel so intimate. I guess it's a place of escape, almost, that it's one of the few places where I would go in and sit down and think, Well, whatever happens, this is going to be brilliant.” </p></div>
<p class="bold">That’s Megan Price. Her parents worked here from the 70s – she was the first Theatr Clwyd baby!<p> 
<p>and she grew up in our youth theatre. She now works as a freelance arts marketing specialist. </p>

:: 46_floorplan_story [nobr]
<p class="bold">The ushers often sneak in to sit here – and see a play changing through the weeks.</p>

<p>Ah, it’s our usher Geoff Wiliams again!</p>

<div class="quote"><p>“You could look at the whole stage and the performance in a different way. You could see things that were going on that you never noticed because you were too busy watching the overall picture. And to watch a thing two or three times, it isn't boring, it's terrific.”</p></div>

