:: 50_story-text-eng [nobr]
<p class="bold">Theatr Clwyd’s mission statement begins like this:</p>

<p>
    <b>
        <i>Once upon a time a group of people stood on a hill<br/>
        and decided to make the world a happier place.</i>
    </b>
</p>

<p>Today, in this beautiful building, people continue that legacy – and keep imagining amazing new ways to keep that vision going.</p>

<div class="quote"><p>“It’s always had a spirit of adventure, I think Theatr Clwyd. It's never sat back on its laurels and gone, oh, we're going to play everything safe. It's never done that, and it’s all the better for it, I think.”</p></div>
<p>That’s Emyr John, one of our amazing creative associates – he runs programmes welcoming young people from a huge variety of different backgrounds, he runs an LGBTQ group, gives history talks, does storytelling workshops for all ages...</p>

<div class="quote"><p>“The theatre staff were very, very helpful. They did all the lighting for us... our own stage manager who was coached by their stage manager, which was excellent... They were absolutely fantastic..”</p></div>
<p>That’s Gina, she was a new mum in the mid-1970s, when she set up the Dee and Alyn Gilbert and Sullivan Society. Haydn Rees invited her to stage a production in Theatr Clwyd’s opening week. </p>
<div class="quote"><p>TheatrClwyd...for me, personally, it's always given me and reminded me of a quiet courage. And I think at its best. That's what it does for an audience, too. You know, in all its shapes, there's always a component in it that has to do with courage... It's empowering.</p></div>
<p>That’s Rhys again</p>
<div class="quote"><p>“The staff were so patient and kind, um, to all the members with disabilities, and everyone else too..it gave us that, that lift-off really..."</p></div>
<p>That’s Catherine Pugh, who co-founded the musical theatre group, Buzz-Ah, who developed a variety of skills for people with or without disabilities and staged lots of productions in our main theatre...</p>

<p>And this is Tamara - Tamara Harvey, she was Theatr Clwyd’s artistic director from 2015 to 2022, and  now co-runs the Royal Shakespeare Company  – </p>

<div class="quote">
    <p>
        “I think what's extraordinary about it is that it shouldn't exist. It it's kind of beautiful madness that it does. It exists because of the passion and tenacity and dedication and vision of a group of people in the 1970s who said our community deserve a voice and then continues to exist because of the passion and vision and tenacity and dedication of continuing groups of people through its history and and so there is a kind of a defiance to it.” 
        
    </p>
</div>
<p>Theatr Clwyd is not one thing. </p>
<p>A group of people stood on the hill, and then another group of people stood on a hill, and then another. They all imagined a better world, and with Theatr Clwyd they made it. Theatr Clwyd doesn’t exist because a group of people imagined, but because people kept on imagining, and will keep on imagining too</p>

<p>That’s the real magic of Theatr Clwyd. <br/>
Where new realities are imagined, crafted and created <br/>
Where we understand our past as a story of transformation that continues into our future <br/>
Where our community shapes us, challenges us, and drives us on - from the bees on our roofs, to the people standing on the hill, looking out and imagining something new - you. <br/>
</p>

